Per Zagat, they have a “raj-era” (colonial) decor. I’d go a step ahead and say that they also have a “raj-era” (colonial) seating policy, wherein all the white Caucasian patrons get seated by the windows/piano, at the front of the house, and all the brown/Indian people get seated in the back of the house, as you can see in the picture I posted.  It took me a hot minute to realize that this was no co-incidence and I was literally living a day in the life of my grandparents under colonial rule in India.  Go here if you want to eat moderately good Indian food at a ridiculously high price with a 1920s colonial “raj-era” racist service.

I wish I could give anything less than 1 star! Awful experience at this overrated pricey restaurant! My husband and I went there on a rainy afternoon and we asked for a glass of hot water. They removed the existing glasses of water from the table and brought Boiling water in small espresso cups! They neither bothered to keep cold water for mixing nor refilled “the espresso cups” until we finished our meal and left! We ordered “Aloo chickpea tikki” and Vegetable Biryani; the Aloo tikki was almost black in color with raw tamarind paste on top instead of the date chutney and tasted so bad that we ate without a word. The biryani was a total shock: for the $18 we paid, we got a small cup of biryani with undercooked  vegetables (the serving vessel was a small cup that held 3/4 cup of rice and vegetables all together); Nobody wants broccoli in the biryani!! We left with the unfinished meal and paid $35 for nothing!! Absolutely worst Indian food we had ever tasted and would never return!! Don’t go here unless you want to just look at the food and leave with a hefty check!

They had local Mumbai and malvani preparations on the menu 😍 We tried Samundari thali which had coconut based prawns curry, grilled salmon, tomamto based fish curry, dal makhani and spinach veggi. Salmon was a winner with charred outside and fall apart tender inside. Also Dal makhani was one of the best though it wasnt the main dish. Malvani chicken ..the name was more authentic than the dish...however we enjoyed the fact that we had Malvanini dish in Washington DC. To end the lunch was sweet platter which had gulabjam. Rabadi, kheer and gajar halwa..which was nice and sweet. The restraurant is chic, is in middle of DC, elegant ambiance and definitely on costlier side.

Bombay Club is always a good place to have an excellent, delicious, reasonably priced dinner in Washington, on the bottom end of Connecticut Avenue within spitting distance of the White House. This restaurant is always reliable, and is always a first-rate experience. On my most recent visit (probably the tenth in recent years) I started with the crispy kale and went on to the grilled seafood dish, matched with an appropriate selection from Bombay Club's wine list. There is a full bar, by the way. If you are not driving, the restaurant is best reached by the Farragut West or Farragut North metro stations (Red Line or Blue/Green/Silver lines).

This place is not worth it. Do not go here, do not waste your time. Upscale place. For what value? I do not know. The staff have an air of superiority and typically look down up on you (Especially if you are Indian) We were tourists looking for a good meal and agree, that we may have been under dressed (shirts and walking shorts, wearing tennis shoes) for the place. First they made us wait for approx 20 min when the table they eventually gave us, was free and ready all the while. In fact, the restaurant was only half full. I guess I should have understood the signal for us to leave. Then we ordered our food and waited a while for the food to arrive in installments. For an upscale place they really don't understand the idea of serving the entire order at the same time. I would have overlooked all these problems if only the food was any good. The chef needs to understand that taste of Indian food is simply not proportional to the volume of spices you use. The entrees were heaped in spices so much that I could hardly taste the ingredients any more. The only things that tasted good was the lemon cashew rice we ordered as sides. we had to order more of these since the rest of the entrees were not necessarily tasty. To top it all off, the waiter, when he presented the check was smart enough to explicitly remind me that I need to put a gratuity when I sign my check. Were you expecting me to not tip you? Save yourself some time and money. Drop this place from your lunch or dinner plans.
